declarations.comments:
Attempts to parse a string as a JSON value. If parsing fails, an error message detailing the
cause may be returned in the `Left` of the result.
declarations.title: parse

declarations.comments: The JSON `null` value.
declarations.title: null

declarations.comments: Converts a `Boolean` into `JSON`.
declarations.title: fromBoolean

declarations.comments:
Converts a `Number` into `JSON`.

The PureScript `Number` type admits infinities and a `NaN` value which are not allowed in JSON,
so when encountered, this function will treat those values as 0.
declarations.title: fromNumber

declarations.comments:
Creates a `Number` into `JSON`, using a fallback `Int` value for cases where the
PureScript number value is not valid for JSON (`NaN`, `infinity`).
declarations.title: fromNumberWithDefault

declarations.comments:
Converts an `Int` into `JSON`.

Note: JSON doesn't have a concept of integers. This is provided
as a convenience to avoid having to convert `Int` to `Number` before creating a `JSON` value.
declarations.title: fromInt

declarations.comments:
Converts a `String` into `JSON`.

**Note**: this does not parse a string as a JSON value, it takes a PureScript string and
produces the corresponding `JSON` value for that string, similar to the other functions like
`fromBoolean` and `fromNumber`.

To take a string that contains printed JSON and turn it into a `JSON` value, see
[`parse`](#v:parse).
declarations.title: fromString

declarations.comments: Converts an array of `JSON` values into `JSON`.
declarations.title: fromArray

declarations.comments: Converts a `JArray` into `JSON`.
declarations.title: fromJArray

declarations.comments: Converts a `JObject` into `JSON`.
declarations.title: fromJObject

declarations.comments:
Performs case analysis on a JSON value.

As the `JSON` type is not a PureScript sum type, pattern matching cannot be used to
discriminate between the potential varieties of value. This function provides an equivalent
mechanism by accepting functions that deal with each variety, similar to an exaustive `case`
statement.

The `Unit` case is for `null` values.
declarations.title: case_

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `Null` if the `JSON` is `null`.
declarations.title: toNull

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `Boolean` if the `JSON` is a boolean.
declarations.title: toBoolean

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `Number` if the `JSON` is a number.
declarations.title: toNumber

declarations.comments:
Converts a `JSON` `Number` into an `Int`.

This is provided for convenience only.
declarations.title: toInt

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `String` if the `JSON` is a string.
declarations.title: toString

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `Array JSON` if the `JSON` is an array.
declarations.title: toArray

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `JArray` if the `JSON` is an array.
declarations.title: toJArray

declarations.comments: Converts a `JSON` value to `Object` if the `JSON` is an object.
declarations.title: toJObject

declarations.comments: Prints a JSON value as a compact (single line) string.
declarations.title: print

declarations.comments: Prints a JSON value as a "pretty" string with newlines and indentation.
declarations.title: printIndented

declarations.title: print

declarations.comments:
Extends the tip of the first path with the second path.

For example, `$.data[0]` extended with `$.info.title` would result in `$.data[0].info.title`.
declarations.title: extend

declarations.comments:
Finds the common prefix of two paths. If they have nothing in common the result will be the
root.
declarations.title: findCommonPrefix

declarations.comments:
Attempts to strip the first path from the start of the second path. `Nothing` is returned if
the second path does not start with the prefix.

For example, stripping a prefix of `$.data[0]` from `$.data[0].info.title` would result in
`$.info.title`.
declarations.title: stripPrefix
